<h2>Outline</h2>
<p>With block encryption we take blocks of data and encrypt each block. DES=
, for example, uses a 64-bit block size (8 bytes) and AES uses a 128-bit bl=
ock size (16 bytes). Often the data will not fill all of the blocks so we n=
eed to pack bytes into the data. We then encrypt, and then decrypt. After t=
his we then unpad the padding bytes.
Three common methods are:</p>
<ul>
<li>PKCS7. This pads with the value which equals the number of padding byte=
s.</li>
<li>ANSI X.923. This pads with a zero value until the last byte, and which =
is the number of padding bytes. This is also known as ZeroLen.</li>
<li>ISO 10126. This pads with random bytes until the last byte, and which d=
efines the number of padding bytes.</li>
    </ul>=20
<h2>Code</h2>
<p>Here is the code:</p>
<pre>package main

import (
	"strconv"
	"github.com/enceve/crypto/pad"
	"fmt"
	"os"
)

func main() {

	msg:=3D"Hello"
	argCount :=3D len(os.Args[1:])
	blocksize :=3D 16

        if (argCount&gt;0) {msg =3D string(os.Args[1])}
        if (argCount&gt;1) {blocksize,_ =3D strconv.Atoi(os.Args[2])}

	m :=3D []byte(msg)
	fmt.Printf("Block size:\t%d bytes (%d bits)\n\n",blocksize, blocksize*8)

	pkcs7 :=3D pad.NewPKCS7(blocksize)
	pad1 :=3D pkcs7.Pad(m)
	fmt.Printf("PKCS7 Pad:\t%x",pad1)
	res,_:=3Dpkcs7.Unpad(pad1)=09
	fmt.Printf("\n Unpad:\t%s",res)

	x923 :=3D pad.NewX923(blocksize)
	pad2 :=3D x923.Pad(m)
	fmt.Printf("\n\nX923 Pad:\t%x",pad2)
	res,_=3Dx923.Unpad(pad2)=09
	fmt.Printf("\n Unpad:\t%s",res)

	ISO10126 :=3D pad.NewISO10126(blocksize,nil)
	pad3 :=3D ISO10126.Pad(m)
	fmt.Printf("\n\nXISO1012 Pad:\t%x",pad3)
	res,_=3DISO10126.Unpad(pad3)=09
	fmt.Printf("\n Unpad:\t%s",res)

}
        </pre>

